            <section class="bleaching-section">
                <h2>
                    <span data-lang="en">Building skeletons</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja">éª¨æ ¼ã‚’ä½œã‚‹</span>
                </h2>
                
                <div class="section-content">
                    <p data-lang="en">
                        Stony corals secrete calcium carbonate (aragonite) from the base of each polyp, creating a cup-shaped structure called a corallite. Over years and generations, these accumulated skeletons form the massive limestone structures we recognize as coral reefs. A single reef can take thousands of years to build.
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        ã‚¤ã‚·ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯å„ãƒãƒªãƒ—ã®åŸºéƒ¨ã‹ã‚‰ç‚­é…¸ã‚«ãƒ«ã‚·ã‚¦ãƒ ï¼ˆã‚¢ãƒ©ã‚´ãƒŠã‚¤ãƒˆï¼‰ã‚’åˆ†æ³Œã—ã€ã€Œå€‹ä½“éª¨æ ¼ï¼ˆcoralliteï¼‰ã€ã¨å‘¼ã°ã‚Œã‚‹æ¯çŠ¶ã®æ§‹é€ ã‚’ä½œã‚‹ã€‚é•·ã„å¹´æœˆã¨ä¸–ä»£ã‚’çµŒã¦ã€è“„ç©ã—ãŸéª¨æ ¼ãŒã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¤ã¨ã„ã†å·¨å¤§ãªçŸ³ç°å²©æ§‹é€ ã‚’å½¢æˆã™ã‚‹ã€‚ä¸€ã¤ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¤ãŒã§ãã‚‹ã¾ã§ã«æ•°åƒå¹´ã‹ã‹ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã‚‚ã‚ã‚‹ã€‚
                    </p>

                    <h3>
                        <span data-lang="en">Growth forms and rates</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">æˆé•·å½¢æ…‹ã¨æˆé•·é€Ÿåº¦</span>
                    </h3>

                    <p data-lang="en">
                        Coral colonies take on different shapes depending on species and environment. Growth rates vary dramatically by form:
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¾¤ä½“ã¯ç¨®ã¨ç’°å¢ƒã«ã‚ˆã£ã¦ç•°ãªã‚‹å½¢æ…‹ã‚’ã¨ã‚‹ã€‚æˆé•·é€Ÿåº¦ã¯å½¢æ…‹ã«ã‚ˆã£ã¦å¤§ããç•°ãªã‚‹ï¼š
                    </p>

                    <!-- Growth forms table -->
                    <div class="table-container">
                        <table class="data-table">
                            <thead>
                                <tr>
                                    <th><span data-lang="en">Growth Form</span><span data-lang="ja">æˆé•·å½¢æ…‹</span></th>
                                    <th><span data-lang="en">Growth Rate</span><span data-lang="ja">æˆé•·é€Ÿåº¦</span></th>
                                    <th><span data-lang="en">Examples</span><span data-lang="ja">ä»£è¡¨ç¨®</span></th>
                                    <th><span data-lang="en">Heat Vulnerability</span><span data-lang="ja">ç†±è„†å¼±æ€§</span></th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">Branching</span><span data-lang="ja">æçŠ¶</span></td>
                                    <td>5â€“30 cm/yr</td>
                                    <td><em>Acropora</em></td>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">High</span><span data-lang="ja">é«˜ã„</span></td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">Tabular</span><span data-lang="ja">ãƒ†ãƒ¼ãƒ–ãƒ«çŠ¶</span></td>
                                    <td>3â€“10 cm/yr</td>
                                    <td><em>Acropora hyacinthus</em></td>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">High</span><span data-lang="ja">é«˜ã„</span></td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">Massive</span><span data-lang="ja">å¡ŠçŠ¶</span></td>
                                    <td>0.3â€“1 cm/yr</td>
                                    <td><em>Porites</em></td>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">Low</span><span data-lang="ja">ä½ã„</span></td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">Encrusting</span><span data-lang="ja">è¢«è¦†çŠ¶</span></td>
                                    <td>0.5â€“2 cm/yr</td>
                                    <td><em>Montipora</em></td>
                                    <td><span data-lang="en">Medium</span><span data-lang="ja">ä¸­ç¨‹åº¦</span></td>
                                </tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>

                    <div class="key-point">
                        <p data-lang="en"><strong>Trade-off:</strong> Fast-growing branching corals create complex habitat quickly but are vulnerable to heat stress and physical damage. Slow-growing massive corals are resilient, but if lost, take decades to centuries to recover.</p>
                        <p data-lang="ja"><strong>ãƒˆãƒ¬ãƒ¼ãƒ‰ã‚ªãƒ•:</strong> æˆé•·ã®é€Ÿã„æçŠ¶ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯çŸ­æœŸé–“ã§è¤‡é›‘ãªç”Ÿæ¯å ´æ‰€ã‚’ä½œã‚‹ãŒã€ç†±ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã‚„ç‰©ç†çš„æå‚·ã«å¼±ã„ã€‚æˆé•·ã®é…ã„å¡ŠçŠ¶ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯è€æ€§ãŒé«˜ã„ãŒã€å¤±ã‚ã‚Œã‚‹ã¨å›å¾©ã«æ•°åå¹´ã‚’è¦ã™ã‚‹ã€‚</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- ç”»åƒãƒ—ãƒ¬ãƒ¼ã‚¹ãƒ›ãƒ«ãƒ€ãƒ¼: æˆé•·å½¢æ…‹æ¯”è¼ƒ -->
                    <figure class="content-figure">
                        <div class="placeholder-image">
                            <span>[ Growth form comparison photos - coming soon ]</span>
                        </div>
                        <figcaption>
                            <span data-lang="en">Four main coral growth forms: branching, tabular, massive, and encrusting.</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">4ã¤ã®ä¸»è¦ãªã‚µãƒ³ã‚´æˆé•·å½¢æ…‹ï¼šæçŠ¶ã€ãƒ†ãƒ¼ãƒ–ãƒ«çŠ¶ã€å¡ŠçŠ¶ã€è¢«è¦†çŠ¶ã€‚</span>
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Section 3: å…±ç”Ÿã§ç”Ÿãã‚‹ -->
            <section class="bleaching-section">
                <h2>
                    <span data-lang="en">Living through symbiosis</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja">å…±ç”Ÿã§ç”Ÿãã‚‹</span>
                </h2>
                
                <div class="section-content">
                    <p data-lang="en">
                        Most reef-building corals host microscopic algae called zooxanthellae (family Symbiodiniaceae) within their tissues. A single square centimeter of coral tissue can contain up to 1 million of these cells.
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        é€ ç¤ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã®å¤šãã¯ã€ç´°èƒå†…ã«è¤è™«è—»ï¼ˆSymbiodiniaceaeç§‘ï¼‰ã¨å‘¼ã°ã‚Œã‚‹å¾®ç´°ãªè—»é¡ã‚’å…±ç”Ÿã•ã›ã¦ã„ã‚‹ã€‚ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´çµ„ç¹”1cmÂ²ã‚ãŸã‚Šæœ€å¤§100ä¸‡ã‚‚ã®è¤è™«è—»ã‚’æœ‰ã™ã‚‹ã€‚
                    </p>

                    <p data-lang="en">
                        This relationship is remarkably efficient. Zooxanthellae use the coral's metabolic waste (COâ‚‚ and nutrients) for photosynthesis, producing organic compounds. Up to 90% of these photosynthetic products are transferred to the host coral. In clear, nutrient-poor tropical waters, this symbiosis allows corals to thrive where other organisms struggle.
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        ã“ã®å…±ç”Ÿé–¢ä¿‚ã¯é©šãã»ã©åŠ¹ç‡çš„ã§ã‚ã‚‹ã€‚è¤è™«è—»ã¯ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã®æ’å‡ºç‰©ï¼ˆCOâ‚‚ã‚„æ „é¤Šå¡©ï¼‰ã‚’ä½¿ã£ã¦å…‰åˆæˆã‚’è¡Œã„ã€ç”Ÿç”£ã—ãŸæœ‰æ©Ÿç‰©ã®æœ€å¤§90%ã‚’å®¿ä¸»ã«ä¾›çµ¦ã™ã‚‹ã€‚ã“ã®å…‰åˆæˆã‚¨ãƒãƒ«ã‚®ãƒ¼ã«ã‚ˆã‚Šã€ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯è²§æ „é¤Šãªç†±å¸¯ã®æµ·ã§ç¹æ „ã§ãã‚‹ã€‚
                    </p>

                    <div class="key-point">
                        <p data-lang="en"><strong>When symbiosis breaks down â†’ bleaching.</strong> Heat stress causes corals to expel their zooxanthellae. The coral loses both its color and its primary energy source. For more details: <a href="bleaching.html">What is Bleaching?</a></p>
                        <p data-lang="ja"><strong>å…±ç”ŸãŒå´©å£Šã™ã‚‹ã¨ â†’ ç™½åŒ–ã€‚</strong> ç†±ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã«ã‚ˆã‚Šã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯è¤è™«è—»ã‚’æ”¾å‡ºã™ã‚‹ã€‚è—»é¡ã‚’å¤±ã£ãŸã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯ã€è‰²ã¨ä¸»è¦ãªã‚¨ãƒãƒ«ã‚®ãƒ¼æºã®ä¸¡æ–¹ã‚’å¤±ã†ã€‚è©³ã—ãã¯: <a href="bleaching.html">ç™½åŒ–ã¨ã¯</a></p>
                    </div>

                    <p data-lang="en">
                        The colors of healthy corals come from both zooxanthellae pigments (browns, yellows, greens) and fluorescent proteins produced by the coral itself (blues, purples, pinks).
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        å¥åº·ãªã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã®è‰²ã¯ã€è¤è™«è—»ã®è‰²ç´ ï¼ˆèŒ¶è‰²ã€é»„è‰²ã€ç·‘è‰²ï¼‰ã¨ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´è‡ªèº«ãŒç”Ÿç”£ã™ã‚‹è›å…‰ã‚¿ãƒ³ãƒ‘ã‚¯è³ªï¼ˆé’ã€ç´«ã€ãƒ”ãƒ³ã‚¯ï¼‰ã«ç”±æ¥ã™ã‚‹ã€‚
                    </p>

                    <!-- ç”»åƒãƒ—ãƒ¬ãƒ¼ã‚¹ãƒ›ãƒ«ãƒ€ãƒ¼: å…±ç”Ÿæ¦‚å¿µå›³ -->
                    <figure class="content-figure diagram">
                        <div class="placeholder-image">
                            <span>[ Symbiosis concept diagram - coming soon ]</span>
                        </div>
                        <figcaption>
                            <span data-lang="en">The coral-zooxanthellae symbiosis: zooxanthellae provide photosynthetic products; the coral provides shelter and nutrients.</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¨è¤è™«è—»ã®å…±ç”Ÿï¼šè¤è™«è—»ã¯å…‰åˆæˆç”£ç‰©ã‚’æä¾›ã—ã€ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯ä½å‡¦ã¨æ „é¤Šã‚’æä¾›ã™ã‚‹ã€‚</span>
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Section 4: ã©ã“ã«ä½ã‚€ã‹ -->
            <section class="bleaching-section">
                <h2>
                    <span data-lang="en">Where corals live</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja">ã©ã“ã«ä½ã‚€ã‹</span>
                </h2>
                
                <div class="section-content">
                    <p data-lang="en">
                        Because reef-building corals depend on zooxanthellae for energy, they require specific conditions:
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        é€ ç¤ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯è¤è™«è—»ã®ã‚¨ãƒãƒ«ã‚®ãƒ¼ã«ä¾å­˜ã™ã‚‹ãŸã‚ã€ç‰¹å®šã®æ¡ä»¶ã‚’å¿…è¦ã¨ã™ã‚‹ï¼š
                    </p>

                    <ul class="habitat-list">
                        <li>
                            <strong data-lang="en">Temperature:</strong>
                            <strong data-lang="ja">æ°´æ¸©:</strong>
                            <span data-lang="en">18â€“30Â°C (optimal 25â€“29Â°C)</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">18ã€œ30Â°Cï¼ˆæœ€é©25ã€œ29Â°Cï¼‰</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong data-lang="en">Light:</strong>
                            <strong data-lang="ja">å…‰:</strong>
                            <span data-lang="en">Sufficient for photosynthesis; typically less than 50m depth</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">å…‰åˆæˆã«å¿…è¦ãªååˆ†ãªå…‰ã€é€šå¸¸ã¯æ°´æ·±50mæœªæº€</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong data-lang="en">Clarity:</strong>
                            <strong data-lang="ja">é€æ˜åº¦:</strong>
                            <span data-lang="en">Low turbidity to allow light penetration</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">å…‰ãŒå±ŠããŸã‚ã®ä½ã„æ¿åº¦</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong data-lang="en">Salinity:</strong>
                            <strong data-lang="ja">å¡©åˆ†:</strong>
                            <span data-lang="en">Normal seawater (32â€“42â€°)</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">é€šå¸¸ã®æµ·æ°´å¡©åˆ†æ¿ƒåº¦ï¼ˆ32ã€œ42â€°ï¼‰</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>
                        <span data-lang="en">Coral distribution in Japan</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">æ—¥æœ¬ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´åˆ†å¸ƒ</span>
                    </h3>

                    <p data-lang="en">
                        Japan lies at the northern limit of coral reef distribution, influenced by the warm Kuroshio Current. True coral reefs (structures built by corals themselves) exist from Okinawa's Sekisei Lagoon to southern Kyushu. High-latitude coral communities (corals growing on non-coral substrate) extend further north to Tateyama (Chiba) on the Pacific side and Tsushima/Iki on the Sea of Japan side.
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        æ—¥æœ¬ã¯ä¸–ç•Œã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´åˆ†å¸ƒã®åŒ—é™åŸŸã«ã‚ãŸã‚‹ã€‚æš–ã‹ã„é»’æ½®ã®å½±éŸ¿ã«ã‚ˆã‚Šã€ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¤ï¼ˆçœŸã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¤ã‚’å½¢æˆã™ã‚‹ã‚‚ã®ï¼‰ã¯æ²–ç¸„ã®çŸ³è¥¿ç¤æ¹–ã‹ã‚‰å—ä¹å·ã¾ã§å­˜åœ¨ã™ã‚‹ã€‚é«˜ç·¯åº¦ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¾¤é›†ï¼ˆéã‚µãƒ³ã‚´åŸºç›¤ã«æˆé•·ã™ã‚‹ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ï¼‰ã¯ã•ã‚‰ã«åŒ—ã«åºƒãŒã‚Šã€å¤ªå¹³æ´‹å´ã§ã¯åƒè‘‰çœŒé¤¨å±±ã€æ—¥æœ¬æµ·å´ã§ã¯å¯¾é¦¬ãƒ»å£±å²ã¾ã§åˆ†å¸ƒã—ã¦ã„ã‚‹ã€‚
                    </p>

                    <p data-lang="en">
                        Japan hosts approximately 400 coral speciesâ€”about half of the world's known species. This reflects the Kuroshio Current's role as a conveyor of tropical larvae to temperate waters.
                    </p>
                    <p data-lang="ja">
                        æ—¥æœ¬è¿‘æµ·ã«ã¯ç´„400ç¨®ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ãŒç”Ÿæ¯ã™ã‚‹ã€‚ã“ã‚Œã¯ä¸–ç•Œã®æ—¢çŸ¥ç¨®ã®ç´„åŠæ•°ã«ã‚ãŸã‚‹ã€‚ã“ã®å¤šæ§˜æ€§ã¯ã€é»’æ½®ãŒç†±å¸¯ã®å¹¼ç”Ÿã‚’æ¸©å¸¯æµ·åŸŸã«é‹ã¶å½¹å‰²ã‚’åæ˜ ã—ã¦ã„ã‚‹ã€‚
                    </p>

                    <div class="key-point">
                        <p data-lang="en"><strong>Northward expansion:</strong> Coral distribution is shifting poleward at approximately 14 km/year due to ocean warming. Corals are now observed in areas like Tateyama, Wakayama, Shizuoka, and even Chiba where they were previously rare. However, this "expansion" does not mean healthy reef ecosystems are followingâ€”the complex ecological functions of coral reefs may not establish at high latitudes.</p>
                        <p data-lang="ja"><strong>åŒ—ä¸Š:</strong> æµ·æ°´æ¸©ä¸Šæ˜‡ã«ã‚ˆã‚Šã€ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã®åˆ†å¸ƒã¯å¹´é–“ç´„14kmã®ãƒšãƒ¼ã‚¹ã§åŒ—ä¸Šã—ã¦ã„ã‚‹ã€‚ã‹ã¤ã¦æ²–ç¸„ã«ã—ã‹ã„ãªã‹ã£ãŸç¨®ãŒã€å’Œæ­Œå±±ã€é™å²¡ã€åƒè‘‰ã§ã‚‚è¦³å¯Ÿã•ã‚Œã‚‹ã‚ˆã†ã«ãªã£ãŸã€‚ã—ã‹ã—ã€ã“ã®ã€ŒåŒ—ä¸Šã€ã¯ã€ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¤ç”Ÿæ…‹ç³»ãŒãã®ã¾ã¾åŒ—ã«ç§»å‹•ã™ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã‚’æ„å‘³ã—ãªã„ã€‚è¦‹é€ƒã™ç”Ÿç‰©ç¨®ã‚„ç”Ÿæ…‹ç³»æ©Ÿèƒ½ã¯è¿½éšã—ãªã„å¯èƒ½æ€§ãŒã‚ã‚‹ã€‚</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- ç”»åƒãƒ—ãƒ¬ãƒ¼ã‚¹ãƒ›ãƒ«ãƒ€ãƒ¼: æ—¥æœ¬ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´åˆ†å¸ƒãƒãƒƒãƒ— -->
                    <figure class="content-figure">
                        <div class="placeholder-image">
                            <span>[ Japan coral distribution map - coming soon ]</span>
                        </div>
                        <figcaption>
                            <span data-lang="en">Coral distribution in Japan: from Sekisei Lagoon (true coral reef) to Tateyama (high-latitude community).</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">æ—¥æœ¬ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´åˆ†å¸ƒï¼šçŸ³è¥¿ç¤æ¹–ï¼ˆçœŸã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¤ï¼‰ã‹ã‚‰é¤¨å±±ï¼ˆé«˜ç·¯åº¦ç¾¤é›†ï¼‰ã¾ã§ã€‚</span>
